 maintaining control over editorial outcomes in the context of AI integration. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (305, 369, 304)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Disclosure of AI usage in manuscripts\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Disclosures of AI usage are required in manuscripts to ensure clarity and accountability throughout the research and publication process. AI policies mandate detailed disclosures about the use of AI technologies, including Generative AI tools, to ensure that readers understand the role of AI in scholarly outputs. This requirement is designed to uphold academic integrity and provide transparency regarding the use of AI in research. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (31, 316, 241, 294)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Rights protection and AI\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Rights protection is a key aspect of AI policies, ensuring that authors and publishers are not subjected to unintended rights transfers when utilizing AI tools or generating content with AI technologies. These policies aim to safeguard intellectual property rights and maintain control over the use of AI-generated content. The overarching goal is to provide clear protections and guidelines that support the interests of both authors and publishers in an evolving AI-driven publishing landscape. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (331, 332, 340)]\"\n        }\n    ]\n}", "input": "\nYou are an expert in academic publishing and AI policy analysis. You are skilled at interpreting complex regulatory frameworks and identifying key stakeholders and their interactions. You are adept at helping people map out the relationships and structural dynamics within academic publishing ecosystems and AI governance policies.\n\n# Goal\nWrite a comprehensive assessment report of a community taking on the role of a Role: A policy analyst that is examining the intersection of AI tools and academic publishing practices, given a text that outlines specific guidelines, responsibilities, and ethical considerations for authors, editors, and peer reviewers. The report will be used to inform stakeholders about the evolving landscape of AI in scholarly communication and to support the development of more inclusive and transparent policies.. The content of this report includes an overview of the community's key entities and relationships.\n\n# Report Structure\nThe report should include the following sections:\n- TITLE: community's name that represents its key entities - title should be short but specific. When possible, include representative named entities in the title.\n- SUMMARY: An executive summary of the community's overall structure, how its entities are related to each other, and significant points associated with its entities.\n- REPORT RATING: A float score between 0-10 that represents the relevance of the text to academic publishing rules, AI policy compliance, ethical guidelines, and institutional accountability, with 1 being trivial or irrelevant and 10 being highly significant, impactful, and essential for understanding and adhering to academic and AI governance standards.\n- RATING EXPLANATION: Give a single sentence explanation of the rating.\n- DETAILED FINDINGS: A list of 5-10 key insights about the community. Each insight should have a short summary followed by multiple paragraphs of explanatory text grounded according to the grounding rules below. Be comprehensive.\n\nReturn output as a well-formed JSON-formatted string with the following format. Don't use any unnecessary escape sequences. The output should be a single JSON object that can be parsed by json.loads.\n    {\n        \"title\": \"<report_title>\",\n        \"summary\": \"<executive_summary>\",\n        \"rating\": <threat_severity_rating>,\n        \"rating_explanation\": \"<rating_explanation>\"\n        \"findings\": \"[{\"summary\":\"<insight_1_summary>\", \"explanation\": \"<insight_1_explanation\"}, {\"summary\":\"<insight_2_summary>\", \"explanation\": \"<insight_2_explanation\"}]\"\n    }\n\n# Grounding Rules\nAfter each paragraph, add data record reference if the content of the paragraph was derived from one or more data records. Reference is in the format of [records: <record_source> (<record_id_list>, ...<record_source> (<record_id_list>)]. If there are more than 10 data records, show the top 10 most relevant records.\nEach paragraph should contain multiple sentences of explanation and concrete examples with specific named entities. All paragraphs must have these references at the start and end. Use \"NONE\" if there are no related roles or records. Everything should be in English.\n\nExample paragraph with references added:\nThis is a paragraph of the output text [records: Entities (1, 2, 3), Claims (2, 5), Relationships (10, 12)]\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n5,ABILA CITY PARK,Abila City Park is the location of the POK rally\n\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n37,ABILA CITY PARK,POK RALLY,Abila City Park is the location of the POK rally\n38,ABILA CITY PARK,POK,POK is holding a rally in Abila City Park\n39,ABILA CITY PARK,POKRALLY,The POKRally is taking place at Abila City Park\n40,ABILA CITY PARK,CENTRAL BULLETIN,Central Bulletin is reporting on the POK rally taking place in Abila City Park\n\nOutput:\n{\n    \"title\": \"Abila City Park and POK Rally\",\n    \"summary\": \"The community revolves around the Abila City Park, which is the location of the POK rally. The park has relationships with POK, POKRALLY, and Central Bulletin, all\nof which are associated with the rally event.\",\n    \"rating\": 5.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact rating is moderate due to the potential for unrest or conflict during the POK rally.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Abila City Park as the central location\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Abila City Park is the central entity in this community, serving as the location for the POK rally. This park is the common link between all other\nentities, suggesting its significance in the community. The park's association with the rally could potentially lead to issues such as public disorder or conflict, depending on the\nnature of the rally and the reactions it provokes. [records: Entities (5), Relationships (37, 38, 39, 40)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"POK's role in the community\",\n            \"explanation\": \"POK is another key entity in this community, being the organizer of the rally at Abila City Park. The nature of POK and its rally could be a potential\nsource of threat, depending on their objectives and the reactions they provoke. The relationship between POK and the park is crucial in understanding the dynamics of this community.\n[records: Relationships (38)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"POKRALLY as a significant event\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The POKRALLY is a significant event taking place at Abila City Park. This event is a key factor in the community's dynamics and could be a potential\nsource of threat, depending on the nature of the rally and the reactions it provokes. The relationship between the rally and the park is crucial in understanding the dynamics of this\ncommunity. [records: Relationships (39)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Role of Central Bulletin\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Central Bulletin is reporting on the POK rally taking place in Abila City Park. This suggests that the event has attracted media attention, which could\namplify its impact on the community. The role of Central Bulletin could be significant in shaping public perception of the event and the entities involved. [records: Relationships\n(40)]\"\n        }\n    ]\n\n}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n----Reports-----\nid,full_content\r\n32,\"# AI Policy and Academic Publishing Stakeholders\n\nThe community centers around AI POLICY, which governs the ethical, transparent, and responsible use of artificial intelligence in academic publishing. Key entities include AUTHORS, EDITORS, PEER REVIEWERS, PUBLISHERS, and various organizations like Elsevier, Taylor & Francis, and MIT Press. These entities are interconnected through relationships emphasizing transparency, authorship, compliance, and ethical use of AI. The policies set by AI POLICY influence how authors disclose AI usage, how editors enforce guidelines, and how publishers manage the publication process.\n\n## AI POLICY as a central governing framework\n\nAI POLICY serves as the central governing framework for the ethical and responsible use of AI in academic publishing. It is developed by major publishers such as Elsevier, Taylor & Francis, and Springer Nature, and it addresses content creation, peer review, and editorial decision-making. This policy ensures that AI technologies are used in a manner that upholds academic integrity, accountability, and ethical standards. [records: Entities (26), Relationships (357, 358, 368, 372)]\n\n## AUTHORSHIP and AI tool restrictions\n\nAuthorship guidelines clearly state that AI tools cannot be listed as authors or co-authors due to their inability to assume ethical, legal, or scientific responsibility. This principle is consistently emphasized across multiple descriptions, including those from BMJ, Elsevier, and De Gruyter Brill. Authors must disclose the use of AI tools in their work, ensuring transparency and maintaining the integrity of scholarly output. [records: Entities (17, 29), Relationships (130, 293, 294, 296)]\n\n## TRANSPARENCY as a core requirement\n\nTransparency is a fundamental requirement in academic publishing, mandating that authors disclose the use of AI tools in manuscripts, particularly in sections like Materials and Methods. Publishers such as BMJ, Taylor & Francis, and Wiley have incorporated these requirements into their policies, ensuring that the role of AI in research is clearly communicated. Transparency also extends to the peer review process, where the use of AI tools must be made explicit to maintain accountability. [records: Entities (13, 29), Relationships (114, 244, 248, 252)]\n\n## COMPLIANCE with AI policies\n\nCompliance with AI policies is essential for maintaining trust, ensuring legal conformity, and upholding ethical responsibilities associated with AI integration in scholarly communication. This includes adherence to data protection laws, intellectual property rights, and the responsible and transparent use of AI. Publishers such as Emerald and Elsevier emphasize compliance, requiring authors and reviewers to verify that the integration of AI technology aligns with established regulatory frameworks. [records: Entities (24, 29), Relationships (111, 347, 351, 354)]\n\n## PUBLISHER's role in enforcing AI policies\n\nPublishers play a critical role in enforcing AI policies, ensuring that all aspects of the publication process adhere to established ethical and legal standards. They are responsible for overseeing the responsible integration and application of AI tools, thereby maintaining the integrity and credibility of scholarly output. For example, Elsevier's AI policy outlines specific guidelines for handling manuscripts involving AI, while MIT Press prohibits the use of AI tools as authors. [records: Entities (37, 29), Relationships (357, 358, 372, 446)]\n\n## ETHICAL USE of AI in academic publishing\n\nThe ethical use of AI is a central focus of AI policies, emphasizing transparency, accountability, and compliance with academic integrity and privacy principles. Publishers such as Elsevier and Emerald integrate ethical use into their AI policies, highlighting responsibility, accountability, and alignment with principles of privacy, confidentiality, and regulatory compliance. This ensures that AI technologies are used responsibly in research and publication processes. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (253, 264, 365, 366)]\n\n## PEER REVIEWER's responsibility in AI governance\n\nPeer reviewers are required to follow AI policies as part of their responsibilities, aligning their practices with broader institutional commitments to responsible AI use in academic publishing. Elsevier's AI policy provides instructions for peer reviewers on the ethical use of AI technologies during the review process, emphasizing the importance of adhering to established guidelines to ensure ethical and transparent evaluation of academic submissions. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (188, 179, 183)]\n\n## EDITORIAL DECISIONS and AI\n\nEditorial decisions must be made exclusively by humans, as per AI policies, ensuring that AI does not play a role in the decision-making process. This policy, specifically outlined in Elsevier's framework, emphasizes human agency and responsibility in editorial functions. The interplay between these two entities highlights a structured approach to maintaining control over editorial outcomes in the context of AI integration. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (305, 369, 304)]\n\n## DISCLOSURE of AI usage in manuscripts\n\nDisclosures of AI usage are required in manuscripts to ensure clarity and accountability throughout the research and publication process. AI policies mandate detailed disclosures about the use of AI technologies, including Generative AI tools, to ensure that readers understand the role of AI in scholarly outputs. This requirement is designed to uphold academic integrity and provide transparency regarding the use of AI in research. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (31, 316, 241, 294)]\n\n## RIGHTS PROTECTION and AI\n\nRights protection is a key aspect of AI policies, ensuring that authors and publishers are not subjected to unintended rights transfers when utilizing AI tools or generating content with AI technologies. These policies aim to safeguard intellectual property rights and maintain control over the use of AI-generated content. The overarching goal is to provide clear protections and guidelines that support the interests of both authors and publishers in an evolving AI-driven publishing landscape. [records: Entities (29, 26), Relationships (331, 332, 340)]\"\r\n\n\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\r\n22,RIGHTS PROTECTION,\"The \"\"RIGHTS PROTECTION\"\" policy refers to a set of guidelines and measures implemented by academic publishers such as Taylor & Francis, Emerald, Wiley, and Elsevier, aimed at ensuring that authors do not inadvertently transfer intellectual property rights or other legal protections to AI technology providers or third parties. These policies are designed to safeguard the originality, ownership, and copyright of authors' work, particularly when AI tools are used in the creation or submission of academic content. The policies emphasize preventing unauthorized use or rights transfer of content generated by AI technologies, requiring authors to verify that AI tools do not infringe on their rights or those of the publisher. They also seek to protect the integrity of submissions and maintain control over the intellectual property associated with academic publications. Overall, RIGHTS PROTECTION serves as a critical mechanism within the academic publishing ecosystem to manage the legal and ethical implications of AI integration in scholarly work.\",20\r\n18,COPYRIGHT HOLDER,\"The \"\"COPYRIGHT HOLDER\"\" refers to the entity that holds the legal rights to a manuscript, submission, or other content, typically the author or the publisher. In some cases, the copyright holder may be the publisher, such as Emerald, Elsevier, or Wiley, depending on the specific agreement between the author and the publishing entity. The copyright may be held by the author, the publisher, or another designated party, contingent upon the terms of the licensing or publication agreement. It is explicitly stated that AI systems cannot hold copyright, as this right is reserved for human entities. The term \"\"COPYRIGHT HOLDER\"\" is used interchangeably with \"\"LEGAL RIGHTS HOLDER\"\" in the context of academic publishing, emphasizing the legal and intellectual property aspects of scholarly works.\",5\r\n141,BMJ,\"BMJ is a publisher of academic journals that has established a policy on the use of AI technologies in content submission and publication\"\"\",5\r\n2,BERA,\"The British Educational Research Association (BERA) is an organization that publishes academic journals and establishes guidelines and policies for ethical research practices, including the responsible and ethical use of artificial intelligence in research and publication. BERA plays a key role in shaping standards for academic integrity and the integration of AI technologies within educational research contexts.\",7\r\n28,COPE,\"The Committee on Publication Ethics (COPE) is an organization that provides guidance on ethical publishing practices, including the use of AI tools in academic publishing. COPE promotes ethical standards in academic publishing and offers guidance on authorship and the ethical use of AI in research and peer review processes. It collaborates with other entities such as WAME and JAMA Network to establish comprehensive guidelines on the responsible integration of AI in academic publishing. As a key stakeholder in the academic publishing ecosystem, COPE plays a critical role in shaping policies and best practices related to the ethical application of artificial intelligence in scholarly communication.\",7\r\n50,WAME,\"The World Association of Medical Editors (WAME) is an organization that supports transparency in the use of artificial intelligence (AI) technologies in academic publishing. WAME collaborates with the Committee on Publication Ethics (COPE) to establish and promote standards for the ethical application of AI within the academic publishing ecosystem. Through this partnership, WAME plays a key role in ensuring responsible and transparent integration of AI tools in scholarly communication.\",3\r\n139,BMJ QUALITY & SAFETY,\"A journal that considers AI technologies as including large language models and other machine learning systems, requiring transparency in their use\"\"\",2\r\n\n\n-----Claims-----\nhuman_readable_id,subject_id,type,status,description\r\n4,COPE,AUTHORSHIP_POLICIES,TRUE,COPE collaborates with organizations such as WAME and the JAMA Network to state that AI tools cannot be listed as authors of a paper\r\n5,COPE,AUTHORSHIP_POLICIES,TRUE,COPE collaborates with organizations such as WAME and the JAMA Network to state that AI tools cannot be listed as authors of a paper\r\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\r\n110,AUTHOR,RIGHTS PROTECTION,\"The AUTHOR, in collaboration with RIGHTS PROTECTION mechanisms, is required to ensure that the use of AI technology does not infringe upon their own rights or those of Wiley, the publisher. Specifically, authors must guarantee that AI tools do not restrict their rights over their submissions or the publisher’s rights regarding the submitted content. This reflects a shared responsibility between the AUTHOR and RIGHTS PROTECTION frameworks to maintain the integrity and legal compliance of academic publishing processes involving AI technologies.\",79\r\n39,AI TECHNOLOGY,RIGHTS PROTECTION,\"AI technology must be used in a manner that safeguards the rights of authors and publishers, including compliance with copyright and data protection laws. It must not infringe upon or restrict the rights of authors or publishers, such as those held by BMJ or Wiley, over their submissions. Rights protection policies are designed to ensure that AI technology respects and upholds these rights throughout its application.\",68\r\n152,AUTHOR,COPYRIGHT HOLDER,\"Authors must ensure that the use of Generative AI tools does not infringe on the rights of the copyright holder, including themselves or Taylor & Francis\",64\r\n153,AUTHOR,BMJ,BMJ requires authors to follow its policy on AI use and disclosure when submitting content,64\r\n331,RIGHTS PROTECTION,AI POLICY,\"The AI policy, including the policies of publishers such as Elsevier and Emerald, is designed to protect the rights of authors and publishers in the context of AI use. These policies aim to ensure that authors and publishers are not subjected to unintended rights transfers when utilizing AI tools or generating content with AI technologies. Specifically, they focus on safeguarding intellectual property rights and maintaining control over the use of AI-generated content. The overarching goal of these AI policies is to provide clear protections and guidelines that support the interests of both authors and publishers in an evolving AI-driven publishing landscape.\",55\r\n34,AI TECHNOLOGY,COPYRIGHT HOLDER,\"AI technology cannot hold copyright due to its lack of legal standing, and it must not infringe on the rights of the copyright holder or Emerald. This highlights the legal and ethical boundaries surrounding the use of AI in content creation, emphasizing the importance of protecting intellectual property and ensuring that AI systems operate within the framework of existing copyright laws. The relationship between AI technology and the copyright holder underscores the need for clear policies that define responsibility and accountability in the context of AI-generated works.\",53\r\n337,RIGHTS PROTECTION,POLICY,Policies aim to protect the rights of authors and publishers from unauthorized use of AI tools,53\r\n230,MANUSCRIPT,RIGHTS PROTECTION,Manuscripts must be protected from unauthorized use of AI technology that could infringe on rights,45\r\n298,AUTHORSHIP,RIGHTS PROTECTION,Authorship guidelines ensure that AI technology does not infringe on the rights of authors,43\r\n185,PEER REVIEWER,RIGHTS PROTECTION,Peer reviewers must ensure that AI tools do not infringe on the rights of authors or publishers,42\r\n9,BERA,AI POLICY,BERA establishes an AI policy to guide ethical and transparent use of AI in academic publishing,42\r\n359,AI POLICY,COPE,\"COPE collaborates with organizations such as WAME and JAMA Network to shape AI policies that govern the ethical use of AI in academic publishing. Additionally, COPE provides guidance on the ethical use of AI tools in academic publishing, which aligns with Emerald's policy. These efforts highlight COPE's role as a key stakeholder in the intersection of AI governance and academic publishing, working both independently and in partnership with other entities to establish ethical standards and best practices for the integration of AI technologies within scholarly communication.\",42\r\n173,EDITOR,RIGHTS PROTECTION,Editors must ensure that the use of AI technology does not infringe on the rights of authors or Wiley,40\r\n378,COPE,POLICY,COPE provides guidance that informs Springer Nature's AI policies,40\r\n212,JOURNAL,RIGHTS PROTECTION,Journals must ensure that the use of AI technology does not infringe on the rights of authors or publishers,39\r\n8,BERA,PEER REVIEW PROCESS,\"BERA mandates that the peer review process remains human-led, with AI only used in limited, disclosed ways\",39\r\n377,COPE,PEER REVIEW PROCESS,\"COPE provides guidance on ethical standards in the peer review process, including AI use\",39\r\n451,POLICY,BMJ,BMJ has established a comprehensive policy on the use of AI technologies in content submission and publication,38\r\n360,AI POLICY,WAME,WAME contributes to AI policies that define ethical standards for the use of AI in academic publishing,38\r\n340,RIGHTS PROTECTION,COMPLIANCE,Compliance with rights protection policies is required to prevent unauthorized use of AI technology,35\r\n90,LLM,RIGHTS PROTECTION,Large Language Models must not infringe on the rights of authors or publishers,35\r\n332,RIGHTS PROTECTION,PUBLISHER,\"Publi